The '''Harrington Research Centre''' is a government-run facility that is part of the AAFC umbrella of the agricultural sector. Located in [[Harrington, Prince Edward Island|Harrington, PEI]],  the centre has a vast wealth of resources all focused on the advancements of Canadian agriculture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/science-and-innovation/research-centres/atlantic-provinces/charlottetown-research-and-development-centre/?id=1180557429228|title=Charlottetown Research and Development Centre|last=Canada|first=Crops and Livestock Research Centre - Charlottetown;Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>

== Potato research ==
PEI has long been an area of Canada that is known for growing quality island-grown potatoes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.peipotato.org/why-pei-potatoes|title=Why PEI Potatoes?|newspaper=PEI Potatoes|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> This has led to the potato industry investing in methods in which potatoes can grow better, and without disease. One disease in particular that was hampered the PEI potato producers in the past decade is the [[Click beetle|wire-worm]]. This spurred scientist Dr. Noronha to create a wireworm trap which severely deterred the pest from affecting nearby potato crops.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-wireworm-pest-problem-trap-invention-1.3487351|title=New wireworm trap for $6M P.E.I. pest problem ''could be a major breakthrough'|newspaper=CBC News|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>

== Organic research ==
Acreage at the facility has been certified organic, becoming the only center in Canada to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-harrington-organic-agriculture-canada-1.3644158|title=Agriculture Canada first: 10 hectares at Harrington certified organic|newspaper=CBC News|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news/science-of-agricultural-innovation/harrington-research-farm-gets-certified-organic-for-organic-research-plots/?id=1465307019073|title=Harrington Research Farm gets certified organic for organic research plots|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>

== Location ==
The research farm is located north of [[Charlottetown]] on 1200 Brackley Point Road.

